## Learn Medicine Article HTML Structure — Required Format

For every future Learn Medicine article, preserve the existing article structure, class names, section arrangement, and ID pattern exactly. Do not introduce alternative wrappers or new class names unless specifically requested.

### 1. Page Head

Every article must include:

* UTF-8 charset
* Responsive viewport
* Metadata for:

  * title
  * date
  * category
  * tags
  * summary
  * featured status
* Article page title ending with `| Learn Medicine`
* Existing stylesheet:

```html
<link rel="stylesheet" href="../assets/css/article.css">
```

* Inter font:

```html
<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Inter:wght@300;400;500;600;700&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
```

### 2. Main Outer Container

All visible page content must be wrapped inside one main container:

```html
<body>

<div class="container">
```

Do not place the article header outside this container.

### 3. Top Home Button

The first visible element inside `.container` must be:

```html
<a href="../index.html" class="home-btn">← Home</a>
```

Do not use longer wording such as “Back to Learn Medicine” unless specifically requested.

### 4. Article Header

Use this exact arrangement:

```html
<header class="article-header">

<div class="article-breadcrumb">
Learn Medicine › Category Name
</div>

<h1>Article Title</h1>

<div class="article-meta">
Added Month Day, Year • Category Name • ~Reading Time
</div>

<p class="article-summary">
Short summary of the article.
</p>

</header>
```

The order must always be:

1. Breadcrumb
2. Article title
3. Article metadata
4. Article summary

Do not add `.article-category`, `.article-subtitle`, extra header containers, or separate breadcrumb links unless specifically requested.

### 5. Article Layout

Immediately after the header, use:

```html
<div class="layout">
```

Inside `.layout`, include exactly:

```html
<nav class="toc">
```

followed by:

```html
<main class="content">
```

The required structure is:

```html
<div class="layout">

<nav class="toc">
...
</nav>

<main class="content">
...
</main>

</div>
```

Do not replace these with:

* `.article-layout`
* `.table-of-contents`
* `.toc-card`
* `.article-content`
* `.main-content`

The existing CSS expects `.layout`, `.toc`, and `.content`.

### 6. Table of Contents

The table of contents must begin with:

```html
<nav class="toc">
<h3>Table of Contents</h3>
```

Each link must point to an existing section ID:

```html
<a href="#overview">Clinical Overview</a>
<a href="#risk-assessment">Risk Assessment</a>
<a href="#treatment">Treatment</a>
<a href="#bottom-line">Bottom Line</a>
<a href="#references">References</a>
```

The order of TOC links must match the order of article sections.

Never include a TOC link unless its corresponding section exists.

### 7. Section IDs

Every major article section must be a direct child of `<main class="content">`:

```html
<section id="overview">
<h2>Clinical Overview</h2>
...
</section>
```

Use short, descriptive, lowercase, kebab-case IDs.

Good examples:

```html
<section id="overview">
<section id="risk-assessment">
<section id="lipid-goals">
<section id="risk-enhancers">
<section id="advanced-testing">
<section id="cac">
<section id="therapy">
<section id="monitoring">
<section id="pearls">
<section id="pitfalls">
<section id="bottom-line">
<section id="references">
```

Avoid unnecessarily long IDs unless they are required to distinguish closely related sections.

The ID must match the TOC link exactly:

```html
<a href="#lipid-goals">Lipid Goals</a>

<section id="lipid-goals">
```

### 8. Section Arrangement

Arrange articles in a logical clinical sequence.

For guideline and management articles, use this general order:

1. Clinical Overview
2. Definitions or Major Changes
3. Risk Assessment or Diagnosis
4. Treatment Thresholds
5. Treatment Goals
6. Risk Enhancers or Special Populations
7. Diagnostic Tests, Biomarkers, or Imaging
8. Treatment Options
9. Monitoring and Follow-Up
10. Clinical Pearls
11. Common Pitfalls
12. Bottom Line
13. References

Do not add every possible detail. Keep the article organized, concise, clinically useful, and appropriate for an internal medicine resident.

### 9. Existing Content Classes

Use the existing article classes whenever appropriate:

```html
<div class="key-point">
```

For central concepts and high-yield summaries.

```html
<div class="clinical-pearl">
```

For bedside pearls and useful clinical nuance.

```html
<div class="warning">
```

For cautions, contraindications, and common mistakes.

```html
<div class="table-wrapper">
<table>
...
</table>
</div>
```

For responsive tables.

```html
<div class="flow-diagram">
```

For stepwise pathways or disease progression.

Do not invent replacement classes such as:

* `.highlight-box`
* `.warning-box`
* `.bottom-line`
* `.formula-box`
* `.medication-grid`
* `.medication-card`
* `.key-points`

unless those classes already exist in `article.css` or the user specifically requests them.

### 10. Bottom of Article

After the last section, but still inside `<main class="content">`, include:

```html
<a href="../index.html" class="back-home">← Back Home</a>
```

Then close the main content and layout:

```html
</main>
</div>
```

### 11. Footer

Use the existing footer class:

```html
<footer class="footer">
Learn Medicine • Article Title • Advanced Resident Review
</footer>
```

Do not use `.article-footer`.

The footer must remain inside the outer `.container`, followed by:

```html
</div>
```

### 12. JavaScript Order

For future articles, include narration first and reading progress second:

```html
<script src="../assets/js/article-narration.js"></script>
<script src="../assets/js/article-progress.js"></script>
```

Place both scripts immediately before:

```html
</body>
</html>
```

